SIMPLE: scripture
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scripture
<hw>Scrip"ture</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>scriptura</ets>, fr. <ets>scribere</ets>, <ets>scriptum</ets>, to
write: cf. OF. <ets>escripture</ets>, <ets>escriture</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧criture</ets>. See <er>Scribe</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Anything written; a writing; a document; an inscription.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have put it in <qex>scripture</qex> and in remembrance.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then the Lord of Manny read the <qex>scripture</qex> on the tomb,
the which was in Latin.</q> <rj><qau>Ld. Berners.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The books of the Old and the New Testament, or of
either of them; the Bible; -- used by way of eminence or distinction,
and chiefly in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is not any action a man ought to do, or to forbear, but the
<qex>Scripture</qex> will give him a clear precept or prohibition for
it.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Compared with the knowledge which the <qex>Scriptures</qex>
contain, every other subject of human inquiry is vanity.</q>
<rj><qau>Buckminster.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A passage from the Bible; a text.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The devil can cite <qex>Scripture</qex> for his purpose.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hanging by the twined thread of one doubtful
<qex>Scripture</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scripturian</ent>⟦br⟧
